{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f9c622e5-e00b-4795-b5d5-ca074240a30d","content":"The project directory doesn't exist here, but here's exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` is the critical property — it packages the console app as a global/local tool.\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name users type.\n- Your `OutputType` must be `Exe` (the default for console apps).\n- No `PackageReference` changes needed — your existing dependencies get bundled automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ff19da53-e57b-4cf1-92fd-48bc65c37192","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist. The user is asking a general question about what they need to configure. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":480,"requestId":"D02C:301399:1588D58:18084B7:6A067439"},"id":"c38ec757-b12e-4a1c-a9d9-57169a9e1001","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:17:54.637Z","parentId":"a6c62a46-476e-4d5b-93c3-d974233e9687"}
